      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        How to Price Your Property for Sale in Brisbane: What Sellers Need to Understand
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Pricing is the single most consequential decision you will make as a seller. Get it right and you create competition. Get it wrong and the market moves on quickly.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Of all the decisions a seller makes during a campaign, none has a greater impact on the final outcome than the price. Not the styling, not the photography, not the choice of sale method. All of those things matter, but they operate within the framework created by your pricing strategy. A property priced correctly attracts the right buyers at the right moment and creates the conditions for competitive tension. A property priced incorrectly can undo everything else that has been done well.</p>

      <p>Understanding how pricing works in practice, and what it means for your campaign, puts you in a far better position to make this decision with confidence rather than anxiety.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How agents determine a price guide</h2>
      <p>The foundation of any credible price guide is comparable sales. Your agent will look at properties of similar size, configuration, land area, and condition that have sold in your suburb or adjacent suburbs, with an emphasis on the most recent transactions. Sales from the past three to six months carry the most weight because they reflect current buyer sentiment and current market conditions. Sales from 18 months ago are useful for context but can be significantly misleading if the market has moved.</p>

      <p>Beyond the raw sale prices of comparable properties, an experienced agent will also consider the days on market for those sales (a property that sold in nine days at strong competition is a different data point than one that sold in 52 days after two price reductions), the discounting rate relative to the original list price, and the volume of current competing listings in your price range and suburb. These factors together tell you not just what properties have been worth but what the buyer pool is currently prepared to pay.</p>

      <p>A credible price guide reflects the market, not the seller's expectations or the agent's aspiration. Agents who inflate their appraisal to win a listing are well known in the industry and the result is almost always a stale campaign and a below-market outcome. When you are interviewing agents, ask them to show you the comparable sales that support their price guide and walk you through their reasoning. Any agent who cannot do this clearly and specifically is not giving you a market-based assessment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The difference between a price guide, a reserve, and an asking price</h2>
      <p>These three terms are often conflated but they serve different purposes.</p>

      <p>A price guide is communicated to buyers during a campaign to indicate the expected selling range. In Queensland, agents are required to provide a price guide within a reasonable range of the seller's genuine expectations. The price guide is not binding but it signals to buyers whether a property is within their budget and whether attending is worth their time.</p>

      <p>A reserve is the minimum price a seller will accept at auction. It is set confidentially before auction day and is not disclosed to buyers. In Brisbane's inner east, most quality residential campaigns use auction as the sale method, which means the reserve rather than an asking price is the critical pricing decision. Setting the reserve too high in an auction context can result in a property being passed in, which resets buyer confidence and typically requires a subsequent private negotiation at a lower price than the reserve that originally felt safe.</p>

      <p>An asking price is used in private treaty campaigns, where the property is listed at a stated price and buyers negotiate from that point. Buyers in Brisbane's inner east generally treat asking prices as an opening position and expect some room to negotiate. The gap between the asking price and the final sale price in a private treaty campaign depends heavily on how well the asking price reflects market evidence.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The danger of overpricing</h2>
      <p>Overpricing is the most consistent and most avoidable mistake sellers make. It is driven by a natural but understandable desire to maximise the outcome, and it is frequently encouraged by agents who inflate their appraisal during the listing pitch. The result in almost every case is the opposite of what the seller intends.</p>

      <p>The first two weeks of any campaign are the most active. This is when buyers who have been monitoring the market are most alert to new listings, when interest is highest, and when the property's novelty has not worn off. An overpriced property will attract low enquiry in this window because experienced buyers and their agents quickly identify the gap between the asking price and comparable sales. They redirect their attention to better-priced alternatives.</p>

      <p>As days on market accumulate, buyer perception shifts. A property that has been on the market for six weeks carries a stigma, rational or not, that something is wrong with it. When the price reduction eventually comes, as it almost always does, the remaining buyer pool sees it as confirmation of overpricing and a further signal to wait. The final sale price in a campaign that required a price reduction is consistently lower than what a well-priced launch from the beginning would have achieved.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The case for competitive pricing</h2>
      <p>Competitive pricing is the deliberate strategy of launching a campaign at or slightly below the upper range of comparable sales, with the goal of attracting a larger buyer pool and creating competition among those buyers. In Brisbane's inner east, where auction clearance rates for well-prepared properties are consistently strong, competitive pricing almost always produces better outcomes than aspirational pricing.</p>

      <p>When a property is priced within the market, informed buyers engage quickly. Open home attendance is stronger. Enquiry volume is higher. The number of parties who proceed to due diligence is larger. And when multiple buyers are competing seriously for the same property, the final price tends to exceed what any individual buyer would have offered in isolation. The mechanism is straightforward: competitive pricing creates the environment for competitive bidding, which is how properties in high-demand suburbs achieve above-market results.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How Brisbane's inner east responds to different pricing strategies</h2>
      <p>Auction is the dominant sale method for family homes and character properties in Brisbane's inner east, and for good reason. The auction process is designed to surface the highest price the market will pay on a specific day, without requiring the seller to commit to a price ceiling in advance. A buyer who is emotionally engaged in the auction room and competing against another genuinely interested party will often exceed what they would have offered in a private negotiation.</p>

      <p>For apartments and units, private treaty or expression of interest is more common, particularly in the sub-$1 million range. In these campaigns, the asking price or price guide does more work in filtering the buyer pool and setting expectations. Setting this price correctly is important because apartments in Brisbane's inner east face a more transparent market: buyers can compare your property directly against similar listings in the same complex or the same street.</p>

      <p>Properties that are genuinely unique, whether through land size, position, or heritage value, are often best suited to expression of interest or tender processes, which allow the market to determine value without anchoring buyers to a stated figure. These campaigns require an agent with experience managing buyers through an open-ended process.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to ask when an agent's appraisal seems high</h2>
      <p>If an agent's appraisal is significantly higher than others you have received, or higher than the evidence from comparable sales seems to support, ask them to show you specifically which sales they are using to justify the figure. A credible agent will be able to walk you through each comparable property, explain the differences between it and yours, and show you how those differences translate into a price adjustment.</p>

      <p>If the agent cannot do this, or if their justification relies heavily on properties that sold more than 12 months ago, properties in different suburbs, or aspirational reasoning rather than market evidence, treat the appraisal with caution. An inflated appraisal is not flattery. It is a commercial strategy to win the listing, and the cost of acting on it is borne entirely by the seller in the form of a longer campaign, lower buyer engagement, and a weaker final price.</p>

      <p>A simpler test: ask the agent what the property would achieve if it sold at auction in four weeks with strong marketing. The answer to that question, grounded in current market evidence, is usually a better indicator of genuine value than any aspirational appraisal figure.</p>

